                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-48-off252 t18300916-48-crimeloc255"></join>. On the 30th of July the prisoner came and took a bed for the night, and on his leaving in the morning, my servant went up stairs and discovered the blankets and sheets had been taken off the bed; she called to the boy, who brought the prisoner back; I was then coming down - he said, "I have taken a blanket and sheet through distress."</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-48-person504">
                  JOHN 
                  HENRY FRASCH
               <interp inst="t18300916-48-person504" type="surname" value="HENRY FRASCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-48-person504" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-48-person504" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I slept in the prosecutor's house,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183009160033"></xptr>and was awoke by the servant crying out, "Stop him, George;" I put on my trousers and came down - the boy had just brought him back; I put him into the parlour - he said, "I have taken a sheet and a blanket, but I did it through distress;" he opened his waistcoat and took them out - the boy fetched the Policeman.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Is it possible I could have them under my waistcoat? A. Yes, I saw you do it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The boy came after me, and said I must go back - the witness was standing at the bottom of the stairs; he went to put on his clothes, and these things were in the parlour - the landlord came down, and said this blanket was worth 10s., and the sheet was fellow to one I had stolen before.</p>
